Tydeverse returns a df

Tidyverse function always returns a data frame. Even if its just one number.


murders |&gt; 
  summarize(rate = sum(total)/sum(population)*100000) |&gt;
  class()

[1] "data.frame"

pull

To get a numeric use pull:


murders |&gt; 
  summarize(rate = sum(total)/sum(population)*100000) |&gt;
  pull(rate) 

[1] 3.034555

Use tidy data with tidyverse functions

Now that the data is tidy, we can use it with other tidyverse functions, such ggplot2:


new_tidy_data |&gt; 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) |&gt;
  ggplot(aes(year, fertility, color = country)) + 
  geom_line()

The lubridate package

CodePlot



Example: group all the polls by week of the year:


polls_us_election_2016 |&gt;  
